In the 1984 film Red Dawn, the invading Soviet and Cuban army entered the United States by first infiltrating the country disguised as civilian illegal immigrants crossing the Mexican border. 
According to the dialogue from Lieutenant Colonel Andy Tanner (played by Powers Boothe) in the film, this strategy allowed the invading force to prepare for the surprise attack:
Infiltration as "Illegals": Tanner explains that the first wave of the invasion consisted of soldiers, mostly Cuban, who crossed the border from Mexico unlawfully.
Sabotage of Defense Systems: These infiltrators specialized in sabotage, attacking Strategic Air Command (SAC) bases across the Southwest and Midwest to destroy missile silos and communication centers before the main invasion began.
Opening the Border: Once these sleeper cells had created enough chaos and neutralized key defenses, they "opened up the door," allowing the main Cuban, Nicaraguan, and Latin American armies to march through the border and advance into the Great Plains.
Simultaneous Strikes: This ground invasion was coordinated with Soviet paratroopers dropping into strategic locations (like the town of Calumet) and nuclear strikes on major cities. 
The film frames this scenario as a response to a weakened United States, where a communist revolution in Mexico and the collapse of NATO allowed the enemy to establish a foothold.
